{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"98459ee1-8e2c-451e-8e1e-010b9b990298","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and hook into the lifecycle events:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created  += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying  += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n\n    // Visibility events (desktop platforms)\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Lifecycle order:**\n\n| Transition | Event |\n|---|---|\n| App launches | `Created` → `Activated` |\n| User switches away | `Deactivated` → `Stopped` |\n| User returns | `Resumed` → `Activated` |\n| App closes | `Destroying` |\n\n> **Tip:** `Backgrounding` fires on iOS/macOS when the app moves to the background — use its `BackgroundingEventArgs` to save state. `Resumed` is the counterpart when returning to the foreground.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8a71bedb-f68a-4169-8fef-a053edd3a8b8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for debugging/logging purposes. This is a general programming knowledge question - I can answer it directly without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":428,"requestId":"9BD4:194916:6288972:6DB98DD:69EC0E9E"},"id":"4aca10da-597e-4351-9392-c22ade573a1e","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:45:27.827Z","parentId":"c4b98c39-61b8-4be8-86d6-c937a302ac2c"}
